<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,268,1806,1832]" pageId="11" pageNumber="12">Mine.</emphasis>
(
<figureCitation box="[285,367,1807,1833]" captionStart="FIGURES 19–28" captionStartId="14.[151,264,1867,1891]" captionTargetBox="[160,1429,189,1834]" captionTargetId="figure-18@14.[151,1435,181,1844]" captionTargetPageId="14" captionText="FIGURES 19–28. Figures 19–22: Melanagromyza achilleacaulis spec. nov.; 19: puparium (indicated by arrow) in Achillea millefolium stem; 20–21: posterior segments of puparium; 20: lateral view; 21: posterior view; 22: posterior spiracles (posterior view). Figures 23–25: M. aenea (Meigen); 23–24: posterior segments of puparium; 23: lateral view; 24: posterior view. 25: posterior spiracles (posterior view). Figures 26–28: M. angeliciphaga Spencer; 26–27: posterior segments of puparium; 26: lateral view; 27: posterior view. 28: posterior spiracles (posterior view)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5158597" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5158597/files/figure.png" pageId="11" pageNumber="12">Fig. 19</figureCitation>
) The larva forms an external stem mine not visible from outside. The larva pupates within the mine constructing a “pupal blister”.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="11.[151,1437,1338,2013]" pageId="11" pageNumber="12">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,328,1878,1904]" pageId="11" pageNumber="12">Puparium.</emphasis>
(
<figureCitation box="[342,476,1879,1905]" captionStart="FIGURES 19–28" captionStartId="14.[151,264,1867,1891]" captionTargetBox="[160,1429,189,1834]" captionTargetId="figure-18@14.[151,1435,181,1844]" captionTargetPageId="14" captionText="FIGURES 19–28. Figures 19–22: Melanagromyza achilleacaulis spec. nov.; 19: puparium (indicated by arrow) in Achillea millefolium stem; 20–21: posterior segments of puparium; 20: lateral view; 21: posterior view; 22: posterior spiracles (posterior view). Figures 23–25: M. aenea (Meigen); 23–24: posterior segments of puparium; 23: lateral view; 24: posterior view. 25: posterior spiracles (posterior view). Figures 26–28: M. angeliciphaga Spencer; 26–27: posterior segments of puparium; 26: lateral view; 27: posterior view. 28: posterior spiracles (posterior view)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5158597" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5158597/files/figure.png" pageId="11" pageNumber="12">Figs. 20–22</figureCitation>
) Straw-coloured, matt, 2.0 mm long, with scarcely visible segmentation; surface quite smooth, except for spine bands. Posterior spiracles set on short protuberances joined towards their bases; brown, each with three large sessile bulbs arranged in one row and brought together. Anal plate is brown, not protruding above the surface of the puparium viewed from the side and directed ventro-posteriorly.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="12.[151,1437,150,1509]" pageId="12" pageNumber="13">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,546,150,176]" pageId="12" pageNumber="13">Cephalopharyngeal skeleton.</emphasis>
(
<figureCitation box="[561,657,150,177]" captionStart="FIGURES 305–311" captionStartId="93.[151,264,1867,1891]" captionTargetBox="[168,1431,203,1825]" captionTargetId="figure-15@93.[151,1435,181,1844]" captionTargetPageId="93" captionText="FIGURES 305–311. Melanagromyza achilleacaulis spec. nov.; 305: cephalopharyngeal skeleton; 306: frontal view of head; 307: head viewed from the side; 308: wing; 309: phallus viewed from below; 310: phallus viewed from the side; 311: ejaculatory apodeme." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5158702" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5158702/files/figure.png" pageId="12" pageNumber="13">Fig. 305</figureCitation>
) Both mouthhooks equal in size, with ventral portion sharply abduct- ed. Each mouthhook bears two accessory teeth. Dental sclerite large, long and waved twice. Intermediate sclerite long, narrow and straight, 1.63× as long as height of the mouthhook. The dorsal cornu bears a large “open” window and narrow arms. Ventral cornu with narrow well sclerotized portion ventrally and wide weakly sclerotized portion dorsally. Indentation index 54.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="12" pageNumber="13" type="distribution">
<paragraph blockId="12.[151,1437,150,1509]" box="[199,663,330,357]" pageId="12" pageNumber="13">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,353,330,356]" pageId="12" pageNumber="13">Distribution.</emphasis>
<collectingCountry box="[359,449,330,356]" name="Ukraine" pageId="12" pageNumber="13">Ukraine</collectingCountry>
(
<collectingRegion box="[464,651,330,357]" country="Ukraine" name="Kharkiv" pageId="12" pageNumber="13">Kharkiv Region</collectingRegion>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="12.[151,1437,150,1509]" pageId="12" pageNumber="13">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,416,366,392]" pageId="12" pageNumber="13">Adult description.</emphasis>
(
<figureCitation box="[431,593,366,392]" captionStart="FIGURES 305–311" captionStartId="93.[151,264,1867,1891]" captionTargetBox="[168,1431,203,1825]" captionTargetId="figure-15@93.[151,1435,181,1844]" captionTargetPageId="93" captionText="FIGURES 305–311. Melanagromyza achilleacaulis spec. nov.; 305: cephalopharyngeal skeleton; 306: frontal view of head; 307: head viewed from the side; 308: wing; 309: phallus viewed from below; 310: phallus viewed from the side; 311: ejaculatory apodeme." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5158702" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5158702/files/figure.png" pageId="12" pageNumber="13">Figs. 306, 307</figureCitation>
) Head brownish-black. Orbit slightly projecting above eye in profile; 3 orb s, 2 fr s; frorb sta in two or three rows, thick, erect between fr s and proclinate ventrally; orbit wide, shining (frontal view); eyes are not haired in male and female; lunule moderately shining, with distinct furrow, is broad but higher than semicircle, reaching the level of the posterior fr s; oc tr large, matt, nearly reaching lunule margin; gena medially 0.17× as high as maximum height of eye; gena deepest in medial part; pped slightly elongated, rounded apically, covered with blackish hairs viewed from the side.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="12.[151,1437,150,1509]" pageId="12" pageNumber="13">
<emphasis box="[199,257,583,608]" italics="true" pageId="12" pageNumber="13">Wing</emphasis>
: (
<figureCitation box="[279,373,582,608]" captionStart="FIGURES 305–311" captionStartId="93.[151,264,1867,1891]" captionTargetBox="[168,1431,203,1825]" captionTargetId="figure-15@93.[151,1435,181,1844]" captionTargetPageId="93" captionText="FIGURES 305–311. Melanagromyza achilleacaulis spec. nov.; 305: cephalopharyngeal skeleton; 306: frontal view of head; 307: head viewed from the side; 308: wing; 309: phallus viewed from below; 310: phallus viewed from the side; 311: ejaculatory apodeme." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5158702" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5158702/files/figure.png" pageId="12" pageNumber="13">Fig. 308</figureCitation>
) Slightly greyish, with uniformly dark grey veins; costa reaching M 
<subScript attach="left" box="[1124,1132,601,615]" fontSize="6" pageId="12" pageNumber="13">1</subScript>
; last section of CuA 
<subScript attach="left" box="[1357,1365,601,615]" fontSize="6" pageId="12" pageNumber="13">1</subScript>
0.75× as long as penultimate; calypter, margin and fringe light brown. Wing length: 2.0 mm in male, 
<quantity box="[1212,1298,618,645]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="2.1" pageId="12" pageNumber="13" unit="mm" value="2.1">2.1 mm</quantity>
in female.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="12.[151,1437,150,1509]" pageId="12" pageNumber="13">
<emphasis box="[199,330,655,680]" italics="true" pageId="12" pageNumber="13">Mesonotum</emphasis>
: Black with bluish undertone, shining viewed from above; sctl and abdomen blackish with distinct yellowish-green shine; 0+2 dc s, posterior longer than anterior; acr s in 6 rows at level of anterior dc s; halter dark brown; legs black, shining as mesonotum.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="12.[151,1437,150,1509]" pageId="12" pageNumber="13">
<emphasis box="[199,365,762,788]" italics="true" pageId="12" pageNumber="13">Male genitalia</emphasis>
: (
<figureCitation box="[389,553,762,788]" captionStart-0="FIGURES 305–311" captionStart-1="FIGURES 312–314" captionStartId-0="93.[151,264,1867,1891]" captionStartId-1="94.[151,264,1685,1709]" captionTargetBox-0="[168,1431,203,1825]" captionTargetBox-1="[157,1393,203,1639]" captionTargetId-0="figure-15@93.[151,1435,181,1844]" captionTargetId-1="figure-18@94.[151,1435,181,1661]" captionTargetPageId-0="93" captionTargetPageId-1="94" captionText-0="FIGURES 305–311. Melanagromyza achilleacaulis spec. nov.; 305: cephalopharyngeal skeleton; 306: frontal view of head; 307: head viewed from the side; 308: wing; 309: phallus viewed from below; 310: phallus viewed from the side; 311: ejaculatory apodeme." captionText-1="FIGURES 312–314. Melanagromyza achilleacaulis spec. nov.; 312: hypandrium and phallus proportionally; 313: epandrium; 314 a–d: female genitalia proportionally; a: egg guide; b: spermathecae; c: proctiger; d: ventral receptacle." figureDoi-0="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5158702" figureDoi-1="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5158704" httpUri-0="https://zenodo.org/record/5158702/files/figure.png" httpUri-1="https://zenodo.org/record/5158704/files/figure.png" pageId="12" pageNumber="13">Figs. 309–313</figureCitation>
) Distiphallus diamond-shaped with two small curved dorsal processes, which are distinctly raised under the surface dorsally viewed from the side and laterally viewed from below. Mesophallus strongly widening distally and slightly widening proximally viewed from the side and below, with small apical invagination viewed from below. Basiphallus 0.46× as long as distiphallus, U-shaped, more sclerotized anteriorly viewed from below. Ejaculatory apodeme with blade subovate and relatively slender base. Epandrium typical for the genus, stout; surstylus bears more than 20 posteroventral sharp spines on inner surface. Hypandrium bears blunt hypandrial apodeme. Phallus 
<quantity box="[482,568,978,1005]" metricMagnitude="-4" metricUnit="m" metricValue="4.0" pageId="12" pageNumber="13" unit="mm" value="0.4">0.4 mm</quantity>
long, 0.53× as long as hypandrium viewed from below.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="12.[151,1437,150,1509]" pageId="12" pageNumber="13">
<emphasis box="[199,401,1014,1040]" italics="true" pageId="12" pageNumber="13">Female genitalia:</emphasis>
(
<figureCitation box="[418,517,1014,1040]" captionStart="FIGURES 312–314" captionStartId="94.[151,264,1685,1709]" captionTargetBox="[157,1393,203,1639]" captionTargetId="figure-18@94.[151,1435,181,1661]" captionTargetPageId="94" captionText="FIGURES 312–314. Melanagromyza achilleacaulis spec. nov.; 312: hypandrium and phallus proportionally; 313: epandrium; 314 a–d: female genitalia proportionally; a: egg guide; b: spermathecae; c: proctiger; d: ventral receptacle." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5158704" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5158704/files/figure.png" pageId="12" pageNumber="13">Fig. 314</figureCitation>
) Egg guide and proctiger are of equal length. Blade of egg guide blunt apically, outer marginal denticles minute, scarcely visible, directed distally; medial membrane without any scales. Proctiger narrow, 4.7× as long as maximum width. Spermathecae brown, oval, unequal in size, one narrower than the other; internal duct invagination 0.7× as deep as height of spermatheca; the width of the smallest 0.75× that of the biggest one. Distinct basal collar present. Spermathecal duct weakly sclerotized.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="12" pageNumber="13" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="12.[151,1437,150,1509]" pageId="12" pageNumber="13">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,335,1194,1220]" pageId="12" pageNumber="13">Comments.</emphasis>
The new species is close to 
<taxonomicName authority="Spencer" authorityName="Spencer" authorityYear="1957" box="[668,1035,1194,1220]" class="Insecta" family="Agromyzidae" genus="Melanagromyza" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="12" pageNumber="13" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="tripolii">
<emphasis box="[668,936,1194,1220]" italics="true" pageId="12" pageNumber="13">Melanagromyza tripolii</emphasis>
Spencer
</taxonomicName>
with the following differences: 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Spencer" authorityYear="1957" class="Insecta" family="Agromyzidae" genus="Melanagromyza" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="12" pageNumber="13" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="tripolii">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="12" pageNumber="13">M. tripolii</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is a larger species with wing length 
<quantity box="[647,734,1230,1257]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="2.8" pageId="12" pageNumber="13" unit="mm" value="2.8">2.8 mm</quantity>
in male, 3.0 mm in female; eyes are haired in both sexes; calypter and fringe silvery-white, margin yellowish-brown; mesonotum and abdomen shining, greenish. Ejaculatory apodeme of the new species is longer, not diamond-shaped (as in 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Spencer" authorityYear="1957" box="[892,1008,1302,1328]" class="Insecta" family="Agromyzidae" genus="Melanagromyza" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="12" pageNumber="13" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="tripolii">
<emphasis box="[892,1008,1302,1328]" italics="true" pageId="12" pageNumber="13">M. tripolii</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
) with parallel margins; surstylus only with group of numerous spines in inner surface, without elongated setae as in 
<emphasis box="[1017,1139,1338,1364]" italics="true" pageId="12" pageNumber="13">
<taxonomicName authorityName="Spencer" authorityYear="1957" box="[1017,1135,1338,1364]" class="Insecta" family="Agromyzidae" genus="Melanagromyza" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="12" pageNumber="13" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="tripolii">M. tripolii</taxonomicName>
.
</emphasis>
In addition the larva of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Spencer" authorityYear="1957" class="Insecta" family="Agromyzidae" genus="Melanagromyza" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="12" pageNumber="13" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="tripolii">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="12" pageNumber="13">M. tripolii</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
feeds as an internal stem borer on 
<taxonomicName authority="(Jacq.) Dobrocz." authorityName="Dobrocz." baseAuthorityName="Jacq." box="[618,1066,1374,1400]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Asteraceae" genus="Tripolium" kingdom="Plantae" order="Asterales" pageId="12" pageNumber="13" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="pannonicum">
<emphasis box="[618,873,1374,1400]" italics="true" pageId="12" pageNumber="13">Tripolium pannonicum</emphasis>
(Jacq.) Dobrocz.
</taxonomicName>
and the posterior spiracles of the puparium each have one small central horn surrounded by 14–18 bulbs (
<bibRefCitation author="Spencer, K. A." box="[960,1119,1410,1437]" pageId="12" pageNumber="13" pagination="3 - 60" refId="ref74583" refString="Spencer, K. A. (1966) A revision of European species of the genera Melanagromyza Hendel and Hexomyza Enderlein, with a supplement on the genus Ophiomyia Braschnikov. Beitrage zur Entomologie, 16 (1 / 2), 3 - 60." type="journal article" year="1966">Spencer 1966</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="12.[151,1437,150,1509]" pageId="12" pageNumber="13">
The new species can be integrated in the key to 
<taxonomicName box="[742,1012,1446,1472]" class="Insecta" family="Agromyzidae" genus="Melanagromyza" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="12" pageNumber="13" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="undetermined">
<emphasis box="[742,923,1446,1472]" italics="true" pageId="12" pageNumber="13">Melanagromyza</emphasis>
species
</taxonomicName>
known to occur in 
<collectingCountry box="[1232,1322,1446,1472]" name="Ukraine" pageId="12" pageNumber="13">Ukraine</collectingCountry>
on p. 413 of 
<bibRefCitation author="Guglya, Yu." box="[182,346,1482,1509]" pageId="12" pageNumber="13" pagination="407 - 414" refId="ref72869" refString="Guglya, Yu. (2016) Four new species of the genus Melanagromyza (Diptera, Agromyzidae) from Ukraine. Vestnik Zoologii, 50 (5), 407 - 414. https: // doi. org / 10.1515 / vzoo- 2016 - 0047" type="journal article" year="2016">Guglya (2016)</bibRefCitation>
as follows:
</paragraph>
